Introduction¶

Ford GoBike is the Bay Area's bike share/bike rental system.This dataset basically contains 183412 bike ride records covering the greater San Francisco Bay area and the features of the rides like duration,the user type,station name etc for the month of february in 2019.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset is made up of 183412 rows and 16 columns where 9 of the columns are numeric in nature,5 are categorical while the rest are time format.

Variables¶

  1. duration_sec : Trip duration

  2. start_station_id : Unique ID of trip start station

  3. start_station_latitude : Latitude of trip start station

  4. start_station_longitude : Longitude of trip start station

  5. end_station_id : Unique ID of trip end station

  6. end_station_latitude : Latitude of trip end station

  7. end_station_longitude : Longitude of trip end station

  8. bike_id : Unique ID of rented bikes

  9. member_birth_year : Birth year of bike user/member

  10. start_station_name : name of trip start station

  11. end_station_name : name of trip end station

  12. user_type : Bike user type(Subscriber - a customer that rented a bike and is more likely to come back for rental again,Customer - a person that rented a bike but might not come back for more rentals)

  13. member_gender : Sex of bike user

  14. bike_share_for_all_trip :

  15. start_time : Trip starting time

  16. end_time : Trip end time

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature of interest in this dataset is the user type of the bikes i.e we want to see how other features contribute to the type of user that rents a bike.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The age of members,their gender,the trip duration,the day of the ride can help support the investigation of the type of user of each bike in the bike share system.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

From the univariate plot on the user type comparison ,it was obvious that there were more of subscribers than customers in february 2019 which is a really great deal for the bike sharing system. As the name implies subscribers are long-term cutsomers of a business (active or not). With the difference between the numnber of subscribers and number of customers,it shows how much users find the bike sharing system beneficial in terms of long and short distance movements.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The age and ride duration were righly skewed with outliers in them,I had to use log transformations and manipulate xticks to show the spread in each variables because the plots were so congested due to large data values.To even use age and ride duration,I had to implement feature engineering where I converted members year of birth to ages and converted ride duration from seconds to minutes to easy data analysis.The year of birth of membered that missing values but I had tof fill the with the mean year because the values are needed for the analysis of the data.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

There is a relationship between days of the week and ride duration in the sense that users ordered bikes on weekends mostly would could contributed to the number of subscribers of the bike sharing systems in the sense people usually go on long distances journeys on weekends so that might lead to them being long lasting customers.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

There were opposite relationships between the ages and ride durations of each user type which I didn't expect because I assumed they would both have negative relationships because for an increase in age,there is supposed to be a decrease in ride duration since older people don't go on long distance journey especially on bikes.

Conclusions¶

The bike sharing system has its advantages and disadvanges but one of its advantages is making transit convenient and flexible. Even if the users of the bikes mostly make their orders on weekdays,mainly Thursdays.With respect to trip duration.This contributes to the engagement of users in using the system for long duration journeys on weekends and shorter ones on weekdays because the weekend journeys are usually occasional while the one on weekdays are more repititive. This benefits is one the reasons subscribers stand out more.
